Doc, first of all, it is good to hear you talk!<br>
I too enjoy the historical revelations and perspectives that have been presented here in recent times.  There has been intelligent and insightful dialogue shared about the contributing parts of the war.  Maybe I'm wrong but I believe that the war is bigger than the sum of its parts.  That doesn't mean that I am opposed to the study of the parts.  It seems then that different people come up with a different total sum.<br>
I am a seething boiling cauldron of emotions that recall facts of physical, mental, and emotional horror.  Many things I did and witnessed in Vietnam are in violation of the values and standards given me by my parents and the small community that I grew up in.  I do not blame myself for participating in the war.. nor do I blame others for starting a war.  Conversely, I regret having had to go.. and I am angry at the &quot;higher&quot; forces that orchestrated the whole event. Pointing the finger, after the fight, does not undo the black eyes and broken teeth.  Maybe..maybe not..it will prevent another fight... OR start another one.<br>
Try not to view me as Neanderthal Man.. ignorant of history or insensitive to the need for corrective thinking, while I expound on the frailty of man to honor his own promisses.  Governments are made up of people, but their is a difference in governments and people.  Most people have a heart and a conscience...governments do not.<br>
Perhaps I am too ademant about protecting the institutions that I hold sacred and sterling (even though they are badly tarnished!)  Still, I believe that looking for answers to our country's faults should be done as a non-destructive inspection!  Praised children seem to rise from their weaknesses..scorned children seem to sink deeper.<br>
Hope you understand me better...I'll drop and give you fifty anyway.<br><br>
Hope you are doing well!!<br><br>
MTF<br>

